 of belief that invested sick and heat with cultural meaning. Illness, with its power to make one's body seem alien, or to link disparate groups of people through contagion, suggested to Victorians the potential instability of social and biological identities. Displacing chaotic social issues onto matters of physiology, they managed a variety of social issues, including questions of race, imperialism, anthropometry, and health. This book explores how Victorian narrative registers fears of psychic and somatic permeability, sympathetic identification with another's pain, and conflicting measures of racial and cultural fitness.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 0aAmerican fictiony19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aDiseases in literature. 0aEnglish fictiony19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aImagination in literature. 0aLiterature and mental illnessxHistoryy19th century. 0aMedicine, Psychosomatic, in literature. 0aMind and body in literature. 0aSomatoform disorders in literature. 4aLiterary Studies -- British. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080476463640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804764636423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780804764636/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles